RIPK3 kinase has a crucial role in the signaling pathways leading to necroptosis, and is implicated in a variety of disease states [37]. At the onset of our small-molecule discovery efforts, we focused on identifying differentiated chemotypes from the HTS that target the inactive state of RIPK3 (Fig. 5
                        a). To successfully implement this strategy, we utilized a full-length construct and a HTRF-binding displacement assay that would be most suitable to identify type II inhibitors that stabilize an inactive conformation [37]. For time-dependence studies, a complex comprising the kinase, probe, and antibody complex was preformed, to which inhibitor was added to determine a 11-point concentration response curve (CRC) at 5 and 60min. A small subset of compounds were identified that might be slow binding; specifically, 44 compounds out of 2571 tested showed aâ¥fivefold shift in IC50 at 5 and 60min (Fig. 5b). For the MOI studies, use of the HTRF platform allowed for utilization of an ATP-competitive HTRF probe displacement as a tool for the mechanistic studies, specifically IC50 shifts between low (1Ã probe Kd
                        ) and high probe (50Ã probe Kd
                        ) concentrations were tested. Results using the full set of triaged compounds (2571) revealed a mix of competitive and mixed-type (noncompetitive or uncompetitive) inhibitors, using a IC50 shift cut-off of 5 (Fig. 5c). These studies were then followed up with more in-depth profiling, including residence time kinetics and full pattern mode of inhibition analyses (matrix of probe and inhibitor concentrations).
